enced during the Dark Ages.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b2a29f63-5c73-4a0d-993a-5573c937fe18","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"The movement first expanded to other Italian city-states, such as Venice, Milan, Bologna, Ferrara and Rome. Then, during the 15th century, Renaissance ideas spread from Italy to France and then throughout western and northern Europe.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"9032bafe-7663-45a2-8b74-de51a1ef26d5","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Although other European countries experienced their Renaissance later than Italy, the impacts were still revolutionary.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"6f27e729-e9be-4e6e-b630-178024bfff0e","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Renaissance Geniuses ","level":2,"id":"renaissance-geniuses"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"4d6aa23f-2c99-49fd-9219-5dcd3bbb875f","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Some of the most famous and groundbreaking Renaissance intellectuals, artists, scientists and writers include the likes of:","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"c7bc7978-3424-4c99-a7f6-3ce4fb6681b1","name":"core/list","attributes":{"ordered":false,"values":""},"innerBlocks":[{"clientId":"e9313afa-0aa0-411e-bcea-e541019a56ed","name":"core/list-item","attributes":{"content":" \u003ca style=\"font-size: var(--fs-body-copy); background-color: var(--c-white); font-family: var(--ff-corpnews);\" href=\"http://www.history.com/topics/leonardo-da-vinci\"\u003eLeonardo da Vinci\u003c/a\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size: var(--fs-body-copy); background-color: var(--c-white); color: initial; font-family: var(--ff-corpnews);\"\u003e (1452–1519): Italian painter, architect, inventor and “Renaissance man” responsible for painting “The Mona Lisa” and “The Last Supper.\u003c/span\u003e "},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"70505763-cde0-44bd-8782-4409ca282d2b","name":"core/list-item","attributes":{"content":" \u003ca style=\"f